    "body": "This is part of the changes in ethers v6, yes. The reason is that if you call `getBlock` with a future block number (a block that hasn't been mined yet), you get `null` as the response.\r\n\r\nAs to how to handle it, that depends on your codebase. You could use a non-null assertion (the `!` operator) if you are sure the block exists:\r\n\r\n```ts\r\nconst block = await ethers.provider.getBlock(blockNumber)\r\nconsole.log(block!.timestamp)\r\n```\r\n\r\nAlternatively, something we do in our codebase is to have a helper that asserts a condition, which IMO is slightly better than using the non-null assertion. For example, you could write an `assertIsNotNull` helper. Check [this example](https://www.typescriptlang.org/play?#). Notice that if you comment out the `assertIsNotNull` call, you get a compiler error.",
